   "source": [
    "The 1st Piola-Kirchoff stress tensor can also be obtained by differentiating the strain energy density function ($\\psi$) with respect to the deformation gradient:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{P} = \\frac{\\partial \\psi}{\\partial \\mathbf{F}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Due to the Cauchy Stress Theorem and the Conservation of momentum:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "F_{\\text{total}} = \\int \\mathbf{P} \\cdot \\mathbf{n}_{\\text{ref}} \\, d\\Omega_{\\text{reference}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $F_\\text{total}$ is the net force across an object's cross section (with normal $\\mathbf{n}_{\\text{ref}}$) required to deform the object. The reference configuration surface is $d\\Omega_{\\text{reference}}$.\n",
    "Thus, the 1st Piola Kirchoff stress tensor is crucial in determining net force for deformation (further explanation/implementation shown in demo XXXX).  "
   ]
